<number box="[905,915,1038,1062]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1.0">1</number>
+ 
<number box="[933,949,1038,1062]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2.0">2</number>
divided longitudinally by median unsclerotized line from base to half; sternite 
<number box="[552,566,1073,1097]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="6.0">6</number>
concave anteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[794,878,1073,1097]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 50" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1748,1771]" captionTargetBox="[161,1420,290,1747]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,286,1747]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 50 (the rotundipennis group). 41 – 45: Neoscutops minor sp. nov.. 41 – 44, male terminalia (paratype): 41, posterodorsal view; 42, lateral view; 43, dorsal view; 44, male sternite 6; 45, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 46 – 50: Neoscutops ranyseae sp. nov.. 46, 47, male terminalia (holotype): 46, posterodorsal view; 47, lateral view; 48, male sternite 6; 49, male tergite 6 and syntergosternite 7 + 8, ventral view; 50, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 41 – 43; 46 – 47 in the same scale." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/200594/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[846,878,1073,1097]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="48.0">48</number>
</figureCitation>
); tergite 
<number box="[975,989,1073,1097]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="6.0">6</number>
and syntergosternite 
<number box="[1227,1241,1073,1097]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="7.0">7</number>
+ 
<number box="[1258,1271,1073,1097]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="8.0">8</number>
fused laterally (
<figureCitation box="[159,245,1110,1134]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 50" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1748,1771]" captionTargetBox="[161,1420,290,1747]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,286,1747]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 50 (the rotundipennis group). 41 – 45: Neoscutops minor sp. nov.. 41 – 44, male terminalia (paratype): 41, posterodorsal view; 42, lateral view; 43, dorsal view; 44, male sternite 6; 45, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 46 – 50: Neoscutops ranyseae sp. nov.. 46, 47, male terminalia (holotype): 46, posterodorsal view; 47, lateral view; 48, male sternite 6; 49, male tergite 6 and syntergosternite 7 + 8, ventral view; 50, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 41 – 43; 46 – 47 in the same scale." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/200594/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[213,245,1110,1134]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="49.0">49</number>
</figureCitation>
). Terminalia: phallus short, slender (
<figureCitation box="[661,746,1110,1134]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 50" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1748,1771]" captionTargetBox="[161,1420,290,1747]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,286,1747]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 50 (the rotundipennis group). 41 – 45: Neoscutops minor sp. nov.. 41 – 44, male terminalia (paratype): 41, posterodorsal view; 42, lateral view; 43, dorsal view; 44, male sternite 6; 45, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 46 – 50: Neoscutops ranyseae sp. nov.. 46, 47, male terminalia (holotype): 46, posterodorsal view; 47, lateral view; 48, male sternite 6; 49, male tergite 6 and syntergosternite 7 + 8, ventral view; 50, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 41 – 43; 46 – 47 in the same scale." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/200594/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[714,746,1110,1134]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="47.0">47</number>
</figureCitation>
); cercus large, membranous, closely approximated (
<figureCitation box="[1337,1423,1110,1134]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 50" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1748,1771]" captionTargetBox="[161,1420,290,1747]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,286,1747]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 50 (the rotundipennis group). 41 – 45: Neoscutops minor sp. nov.. 41 – 44, male terminalia (paratype): 41, posterodorsal view; 42, lateral view; 43, dorsal view; 44, male sternite 6; 45, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 46 – 50: Neoscutops ranyseae sp. nov.. 46, 47, male terminalia (holotype): 46, posterodorsal view; 47, lateral view; 48, male sternite 6; 49, male tergite 6 and syntergosternite 7 + 8, ventral view; 50, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 41 – 43; 46 – 47 in the same scale." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/200594/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[1391,1423,1110,1134]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="46.0">46</number>
</figureCitation>
); postgonites short (
<figureCitation box="[361,448,1145,1169]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 50" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1748,1771]" captionTargetBox="[161,1420,290,1747]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,286,1747]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 50 (the rotundipennis group). 41 – 45: Neoscutops minor sp. nov.. 41 – 44, male terminalia (paratype): 41, posterodorsal view; 42, lateral view; 43, dorsal view; 44, male sternite 6; 45, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 46 – 50: Neoscutops ranyseae sp. nov.. 46, 47, male terminalia (holotype): 46, posterodorsal view; 47, lateral view; 48, male sternite 6; 49, male tergite 6 and syntergosternite 7 + 8, ventral view; 50, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 41 – 43; 46 – 47 in the same scale." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/200594/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[416,448,1145,1169]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="46.0">46</number>
</figureCitation>
); surstylus contiguous with epandrium, not articulated (
<figureCitation box="[1088,1230,1145,1169]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 50" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1748,1771]" captionTargetBox="[161,1420,290,1747]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,286,1747]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 50 (the rotundipennis group). 41 – 45: Neoscutops minor sp. nov.. 41 – 44, male terminalia (paratype): 41, posterodorsal view; 42, lateral view; 43, dorsal view; 44, male sternite 6; 45, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 46 – 50: Neoscutops ranyseae sp. nov.. 46, 47, male terminalia (holotype): 46, posterodorsal view; 47, lateral view; 48, male sternite 6; 49, male tergite 6 and syntergosternite 7 + 8, ventral view; 50, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 41 – 43; 46 – 47 in the same scale." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/200594/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Figs. 46, 47</figureCitation>
); ejaculatory apodeme small, elongate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,1254,1961]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,1254,1278]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Female.</emphasis>
As in the male except for clypeus brown on apex. Terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[995,1079,1254,1278]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 50" captionStartId="18.[151,264,1748,1771]" captionTargetBox="[161,1420,290,1747]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,286,1747]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 50 (the rotundipennis group). 41 – 45: Neoscutops minor sp. nov.. 41 – 44, male terminalia (paratype): 41, posterodorsal view; 42, lateral view; 43, dorsal view; 44, male sternite 6; 45, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 46 – 50: Neoscutops ranyseae sp. nov.. 46, 47, male terminalia (holotype): 46, posterodorsal view; 47, lateral view; 48, male sternite 6; 49, male tergite 6 and syntergosternite 7 + 8, ventral view; 50, female terminalia, posteroventral view. Figs. 41 – 43; 46 – 47 in the same scale." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/200594/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[1047,1079,1254,1278]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="50.0">50</number>
</figureCitation>
): syntergosternite 
<number box="[1284,1298,1255,1278]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="7.0">7</number>
well sclerotized; sternite 
<number box="[310,324,1289,1313]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="8.0">8</number>
rather triangular, distal margin slightly concave in middle; hypoproct wide and short, anterior margin with small median cleft; cercus small.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
